WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.300 --> 00:00:04.305
Prof: So I want to
continue talking today about

00:00:04.305 --> 00:00:07.764
land use and the special problem
that we face in managing land

00:00:07.764 --> 00:00:10.260
use and development in the
coastal zone.

00:00:10.260 --> 00:00:12.120
Why the coastal zone?
 

00:00:12.120 --> 00:00:14.570
Well, for several really
important reasons.

00:00:14.570 --> 00:00:17.960
One is that it's under enormous
development pressure.

00:00:17.960 --> 00:00:21.560
People often want to live in
urban areas.

00:00:21.560 --> 00:00:24.840
They often want to live in
coastal environments.

00:00:24.840 --> 00:00:29.558
But also, a coastal zone is
experiencing increased risk of

00:00:29.558 --> 00:00:32.337
damage from storms,
sea level rise,

00:00:32.337 --> 00:00:36.230
and increased pollution that's
also associated with density.

00:00:36.230 --> 00:00:39.970
So I want to talk today about
the variety of strategies that

00:00:39.970 --> 00:00:43.710
might be used to control
development in the coastal zone.

00:00:43.710 --> 00:00:48.000
So I thought I'd start out with
a little cartoon.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:50.338
Good news, at the current rate
of global warming,

00:00:50.338 --> 00:00:53.359
we should be able to just swim
over there and eat them in under

00:00:53.359 --> 00:00:54.090
five years.
 

00:00:54.090 --> 00:00:59.470
So within the world,
640,650 million people live in

00:00:59.470 --> 00:01:05.603
the coastal zone that are at
some risk of property loss or

00:01:05.603 --> 00:01:08.938
injury from intense storms.
 

00:01:08.938 --> 00:01:12.751
And the ten countries with the
largest number of people living

00:01:12.751 --> 00:01:16.438
in vulnerable low-elevation
coastal zones include China,

00:01:16.438 --> 00:01:19.019
India, Bangladesh,
Vietnam, Indonesia,

00:01:19.019 --> 00:01:21.301
Japan, Egypt,
the U.S., Thailand and the

00:01:21.301 --> 00:01:22.120
Philippines.
 

00:01:22.120 --> 00:01:26.390
So that the overwhelming
majority of people that live in

00:01:26.390 --> 00:01:31.281
the coastal zone in the world do
not have the capacity to manage

00:01:31.281 --> 00:01:33.690
the hazards that they face.
 

00:01:33.690 --> 00:01:38.830
And the variety of legal and
economic strategies that might

00:01:38.830 --> 00:01:43.616
be used to prevent serious
damage is the subject of the

00:01:43.616 --> 00:01:44.680
lecture.
 

00:01:44.680 --> 00:01:50.301
So the growth of cities in the
coastal zone is a significant

00:01:50.301 --> 00:01:52.970
issue to pay attention to.
 

00:01:52.970 --> 00:01:54.860
So that on average,
coastal cities are growing

00:01:54.860 --> 00:01:57.340
twenty percent faster than any
other cities in the world.

00:01:57.340 --> 00:02:00.522
And they have ten to fifteen
percent higher densities than

00:02:00.522 --> 00:02:01.358
other cities.
 

00:02:01.358 --> 00:02:04.599
And of the twenty megacities in
the world, fifteen of them are

00:02:04.599 --> 00:02:05.608
in coastal areas.
 

00:02:05.608 --> 00:02:08.556
Now, within the U.S.,
we have a statute called the

00:02:08.556 --> 00:02:10.360
Coastal Zone Management Act.
 

00:02:10.360 --> 00:02:13.677
And the act is administered by
the National Oceanic and

00:02:13.677 --> 00:02:15.460
Atmospheric Administration.
 

00:02:15.460 --> 00:02:20.110
And it provides for management
of the nation's coastal zones as

00:02:20.110 --> 00:02:22.810
well as the resources found
there.

00:02:22.810 --> 00:02:26.878
And it includes the Great
Lakes, as well as the sea coast.

00:02:26.878 --> 00:02:31.141
And it's designed to balance
economic development and promote

00:02:31.141 --> 00:02:34.907
economic development at the same
time that it promotes

00:02:34.907 --> 00:02:37.110
environmental conservation.
 

00:02:37.110 --> 00:02:38.848
So it has a tension built into
the mission statement of the

00:02:38.848 --> 00:02:39.150
statute.
 

00:02:39.150 --> 00:02:42.613
Now, there was great debate
within the Nixon Administration

00:02:42.613 --> 00:02:46.016
about the structure of this
statute and what kind of teeth

00:02:46.016 --> 00:02:47.508
would be put into it.
 

00:02:47.508 --> 00:02:50.562
Should the federal government
get involved in the regulation

00:02:50.562 --> 00:02:53.091
of land use,
the way that the State of New

00:02:53.091 --> 00:02:56.351
York got involved in the
regulation of private land use

00:02:56.351 --> 00:02:57.680
in the Adirondacks?
 

00:02:57.680 --> 00:03:02.620
And there were forces inside
the Nixon Administration,

00:03:02.620 --> 00:03:05.280
Republican administration,
you'll recall,

00:03:05.280 --> 00:03:10.030
that argued quite extensively
that we needed to protect land

00:03:10.030 --> 00:03:14.780
areas in the coastal zone and
that the cost to the nation in

00:03:14.780 --> 00:03:19.530
terms of bearing liability and
responsibility for rebuilding

00:03:19.530 --> 00:03:24.038
damaged areas was growing and
was going to be potentially

00:03:24.038 --> 00:03:25.729
overwhelming.
 

00:03:25.729 --> 00:03:30.060
So that the overall objectives
are conflicting and include the

00:03:30.060 --> 00:03:31.917
phrase,
"preserve,

00:03:31.917 --> 00:03:34.246
protect, develop,
and where possible,

00:03:34.246 --> 00:03:36.554
to restore or enhance the
resources of the nation's

00:03:36.554 --> 00:03:37.568
coastal zone."
 

00:03:37.568 --> 00:03:42.176
We also have a coincidental
statute that's created the

00:03:42.176 --> 00:03:45.220
National Flood Insurance
Program.

00:03:45.220 --> 00:03:49.449
But that program is now
essentially bankrupt.

00:03:49.449 --> 00:03:53.662
So the Federal Flood Insurance
Program faces major financial

00:03:53.662 --> 00:03:56.730
difficulties,
particularly as the Gulf Coast

00:03:56.730 --> 00:03:57.660
recovers.
 

00:03:57.660 --> 00:03:59.139
It's essentially bankrupt.
 

00:03:59.139 --> 00:04:02.187
The Federal Emergency
Management Agency officials

00:04:02.187 --> 00:04:06.122
estimate that Hurricanes Katrina
and Rita together would result

00:04:06.122 --> 00:04:09.550
in flood insurance claims of
about twenty-three billion

00:04:09.550 --> 00:04:10.438
dollars.
 

00:04:10.438 --> 00:04:15.264
Well it turns out that when you
total up the costs of emergency

00:04:15.264 --> 00:04:18.336
response,
property restoration,

00:04:18.336 --> 00:04:23.629
the healthcare requirements
associated with these two

00:04:23.629 --> 00:04:26.095
storms,
it's not twenty three billion

00:04:26.095 --> 00:04:27.843
dollars,
it's in the hundreds of

00:04:27.843 --> 00:04:29.740
billions of dollars that the
U.S.

00:04:29.740 --> 00:04:31.069
government expended.
 

00:04:31.069 --> 00:04:36.699
So should coastal property be
insured by the public sector?

00:04:36.699 --> 00:04:39.459
What kinds of alternatives
might there be?

00:04:39.459 --> 00:04:44.041
And the Federal Flood Insurance
Program has encouraged people to

00:04:44.041 --> 00:04:47.459
build in the coastal areas that
are at risk,

00:04:47.459 --> 00:04:51.240
and it offers them a subsidized
low rate of insurance.

00:04:51.240 --> 00:04:55.291
So that in the event of storm
damage, property damage,

00:04:55.291 --> 00:04:59.495
flooding, the government steps
in and basically provides

00:04:59.495 --> 00:05:02.629
low-cost insurance so people
rebuild.

00:05:02.629 --> 00:05:05.291
So what are the variety of
management strategies that you

00:05:05.291 --> 00:05:07.860
might use, the different kinds
of legal instruments?

00:05:07.860 --> 00:05:10.439
Well, there are certain
questions that you might

00:05:10.439 --> 00:05:10.990
address.
 

00:05:10.990 --> 00:05:13.954
You know, how should we go
about protecting open lands in

00:05:13.954 --> 00:05:14.959
the coastal area?
 

00:05:14.959 --> 00:05:16.660
Should they be public?
 

00:05:16.660 --> 00:05:17.649
Should they be private?
 

00:05:17.649 --> 00:05:20.410
Should we employ land use
regulation?

00:05:20.410 --> 00:05:23.997
Should it be managed by local
governments as it traditionally

00:05:23.997 --> 00:05:26.930
has been through much of the
twentieth century?

00:05:26.930 --> 00:05:28.160
State governments?
 

00:05:28.160 --> 00:05:30.449
Or should the federal
government step in?

00:05:30.449 --> 00:05:33.648
And I'll give you a couple of
examples over the next 45

00:05:33.648 --> 00:05:36.964
minutes that will show you how
the federal government has

00:05:36.964 --> 00:05:40.637
stepped in and applied eminent
domain to purchase up open areas

00:05:40.637 --> 00:05:43.303
and resources that the
government thought were

00:05:43.303 --> 00:05:46.680
particularly valuable,
not just because of their

00:05:46.680 --> 00:05:50.497
ecological characteristics,
but also because they provided

00:05:50.497 --> 00:05:54.521
recreational opportunities,
particularly in the vicinity of

00:05:54.521 --> 00:05:56.250
these population centers.
 

00:05:56.250 --> 00:05:59.449
So insurance,
whether or not the insurance

00:05:59.449 --> 00:06:03.822
program should be continued,
whether or not the subsidies

00:06:03.822 --> 00:06:07.569
should be removed,
this is an open question.

00:06:07.569 --> 00:06:09.629
How about transferable
development rights?

00:06:09.629 --> 00:06:13.675
I'll speak about this in a few
moments, but the idea behind

00:06:13.675 --> 00:06:18.209
transferable development rights
is that you have a source zone.

00:06:18.209 --> 00:06:22.994
So that if a zone is set up,
a zoning scheme is set up and

00:06:22.994 --> 00:06:28.029
one area is more restricted to
limit development than another

00:06:28.029 --> 00:06:31.127
area,
the restricted area might have

00:06:31.127 --> 00:06:35.492
some sort of a scheme where they
could transfer a credit to

00:06:35.492 --> 00:06:39.029
develop to another area or a
receiving zone.

00:06:39.029 --> 00:06:42.086
So you might think about it as
having a sending zone and a

00:06:42.086 --> 00:06:43.000
receiving zone.
 

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:45.848
So that if you are restricted,
you can't build on your

00:06:45.848 --> 00:06:48.750
property because you're lying
within a flood plain,

00:06:48.750 --> 00:06:52.637
you're lying say adjacent to a
wetland or next to the

00:06:52.637 --> 00:06:54.786
shoreline,
then you don't lose your

00:06:54.786 --> 00:06:55.569
property value.
 

00:06:55.569 --> 00:06:59.050
So that this idea of
transferable development rights

00:06:59.050 --> 00:07:02.939
does an end run around the
question about compensation.

00:07:02.939 --> 00:07:07.444
So that it avoids the
possibility of litigation based

00:07:07.444 --> 00:07:12.470
upon the Fifth Amendment that we
described, went through on

00:07:12.470 --> 00:07:13.509
Tuesday.
 

00:07:13.509 --> 00:07:17.303
So thinking about-- you see,
I've repeated insurance twice

00:07:17.303 --> 00:07:17.769
here.
 

00:07:17.769 --> 00:07:19.670
Thinking about the idea of
easements.

00:07:19.670 --> 00:07:22.420
So that the government could go
into an area and buy up some of

00:07:22.420 --> 00:07:24.329
the development rights but not
all of it.

00:07:24.329 --> 00:07:29.468
So the complete bundle of
rights might be broken up into

00:07:29.468 --> 00:07:31.149
bits and pieces.
 

00:07:31.149 --> 00:07:34.754
You could also imagine a
statute that would employ a

00:07:34.754 --> 00:07:37.230
variety of different tax
schemes.

00:07:37.230 --> 00:07:41.329
They might be property tax
related, so that property taxes

00:07:41.329 --> 00:07:45.500
could be elevated in areas that
are especially valuable.

00:07:45.500 --> 00:07:49.363
And they might be lower in
areas that are further away from

00:07:49.363 --> 00:07:52.029
the coast, outside of the hazard
zone.

00:07:52.029 --> 00:07:54.829
And you might think also about
income tax credits.

00:07:54.829 --> 00:07:58.422
I mean, what if you received an
income tax credit when you

00:07:58.422 --> 00:08:01.509
purchased property that was in a
low-risk area?

00:08:01.509 --> 00:08:04.519
Or in an area that had lower
resource values?

00:08:04.519 --> 00:08:09.329
And also, the idea of payment
for ecosystem services.

00:08:09.329 --> 00:08:11.079
Now, what would that mean?
 

00:08:11.079 --> 00:08:12.550
What are ecosystem services?
 

00:08:12.550 --> 00:08:15.985
Well, I mean,
the coastal zone in its natural

00:08:15.985 --> 00:08:19.028
condition plays many different
roles.

00:08:19.028 --> 00:08:22.935
And I'll show you some photos
in a moment that demonstrate the

00:08:22.935 --> 00:08:26.165
flood storage capacity,
but also the biological

00:08:26.165 --> 00:08:29.160
diversity is often higher in
coastal areas.

00:08:29.160 --> 00:08:31.812
And also recreational
opportunities,

00:08:31.812 --> 00:08:35.148
marine fisheries,
the commercial value of the

00:08:35.148 --> 00:08:38.178
coastal zone is extremely
important.

00:08:38.178 --> 00:08:43.267
Nearly seventy-five percent of
marine fisheries that are

00:08:43.267 --> 00:08:49.001
commercially caught spend some
portion of their life in coastal

00:08:49.001 --> 00:08:52.340
estuaries,
in wetlands areas.

00:08:52.340 --> 00:08:56.570
And many of the coastlines of
the United States,

00:08:56.570 --> 00:09:02.058
they're ringed by thin bands of
sand that are known as barrier

00:09:02.058 --> 00:09:03.139
islands.
 

00:09:03.139 --> 00:09:08.971
And these barriers basically
act to protect the inland areas

00:09:08.971 --> 00:09:11.740
from intense storm damage.
 

00:09:11.740 --> 00:09:15.662
So that thinking about the
variety of protective services

00:09:15.662 --> 00:09:20.076
and recreational and commercial
opportunities in addition to the

00:09:20.076 --> 00:09:24.208
property value opportunities
that most local governments are

00:09:24.208 --> 00:09:25.399
looking at.
 

00:09:25.399 --> 00:09:26.960
And why would that be?
 

00:09:26.960 --> 00:09:31.082
Well local governments get
their primary source of tax

00:09:31.082 --> 00:09:35.517
revenue to offer all of their
services predominately based

00:09:35.517 --> 00:09:38.240
upon the valuation of property.
 

00:09:38.240 --> 00:09:41.019
So as development increases in
any town,

00:09:41.019 --> 00:09:44.023
in any municipality,
it offers increased opportunity

00:09:44.023 --> 00:09:47.380
for a local or a municipal
government to secure additional

00:09:47.380 --> 00:09:47.970
taxes.
 

00:09:47.970 --> 00:09:50.950
So payments for ecosystem
services.

00:09:50.950 --> 00:09:52.808
Now what might that be?
 

00:09:52.808 --> 00:09:58.942
Well, supposing you have
someone who wants to develop in

00:09:58.942 --> 00:10:02.602
a wetland area,
and you have created a

00:10:02.602 --> 00:10:06.888
regulation or a statute that
offers specific protection of

00:10:06.888 --> 00:10:07.788
wetlands.
 

00:10:07.788 --> 00:10:12.620
And wetlands are protected in
the United States under the

00:10:12.620 --> 00:10:16.847
Clean Water Act if they're
adjacent to a navigable

00:10:16.847 --> 00:10:17.970
waterway.
 

00:10:17.970 --> 00:10:21.009
But many states have also
adopted their own protective

00:10:21.009 --> 00:10:22.100
wetland statutes.
 

00:10:22.100 --> 00:10:24.980
And many local governments have
also filed suit.

00:10:24.980 --> 00:10:29.182
So these areas that are
seasonally wet or marshy or

00:10:29.182 --> 00:10:32.628
parts of estuaries,
they get special legal

00:10:32.628 --> 00:10:35.570
attention in the United States.
 

00:10:35.570 --> 00:10:40.715
So now imagine that you decided
that you wanted to curtail any

00:10:40.715 --> 00:10:46.029
future development in a wetland
or an endangered species habitat

00:10:46.029 --> 00:10:47.970
or in a flood zone.
 

00:10:47.970 --> 00:10:51.082
Well, basically,
if somebody wanted to develop

00:10:51.082 --> 00:10:54.956
there, you might give them a
credit so that they could do

00:10:54.956 --> 00:10:55.580
that.
 

00:10:55.580 --> 00:10:57.899
They may have to pay extra.
 

00:10:57.899 --> 00:11:01.688
And that money could go into a
bank, basically an ecosystem

00:11:01.688 --> 00:11:02.668
service bank.
 

00:11:02.668 --> 00:11:05.721
And there are now banks that
have been created in the United

00:11:05.721 --> 00:11:08.928
States and in different parts of
the world where developers are

00:11:08.928 --> 00:11:11.830
developing in sensitive areas,
they're allowed to do that.

00:11:11.830 --> 00:11:17.004
But they have to pay into this
bank and then that money is used

00:11:17.004 --> 00:11:21.009
to restore resources that have
been degraded,

00:11:21.009 --> 00:11:23.428
perhaps in the same watershed,
perhaps in the same

00:11:23.428 --> 00:11:24.168
municipality.
 

00:11:24.168 --> 00:11:31.822
Or the funds might be used to
purchase land to offer greater

00:11:31.822 --> 00:11:33.509
protection.
 

00:11:33.509 --> 00:11:37.259
And the trade is rarely
conducted on an acre per acre or

00:11:37.259 --> 00:11:39.168
hectare per hectare basis.
 

00:11:39.168 --> 00:11:43.678
Normally, you require the
developer to pay for protection

00:11:43.678 --> 00:11:48.509
at some multiple of the scale of
the original development.

00:11:48.509 --> 00:11:52.870
So it might be a one for three,
or one for four acre trade.

00:11:52.870 --> 00:11:56.405
The developer gets to develop
one acre but then he's literally

00:11:56.405 --> 00:11:58.899
financing the protection of
another area.

00:11:58.899 --> 00:12:03.510
So this form of credit creation
and purchase and banking is

00:12:03.510 --> 00:12:07.090
becoming much more common around
the world.

00:12:07.090 --> 00:12:10.485
And if you think about the
similarity to this between the

00:12:10.485 --> 00:12:13.820
cap in trade idea that we
discussed when we were talking

00:12:13.820 --> 00:12:17.580
about the Clean Air Act and the
sulfur dioxide provisions.

00:12:17.580 --> 00:12:21.028
Remember that in the Ohio
Valley and up through the

00:12:21.028 --> 00:12:24.649
northeastern United States,
you had this cap put on

00:12:24.649 --> 00:12:28.086
CO_2 emission
allowances for all the power

00:12:28.086 --> 00:12:28.759
plants.
 

00:12:28.759 --> 00:12:34.779
And that allowed a trading
scheme to evolve so that as the

00:12:34.779 --> 00:12:40.798
ceiling for total allowable
SO_2 diminished,

00:12:40.798 --> 00:12:45.168
it made the allowances much
more valuable.

00:12:45.168 --> 00:12:50.375
So that those that emitted the
lowest levels of SO_2

00:12:50.375 --> 00:12:55.581
received credits that they could
then sell to those industries

00:12:55.581 --> 00:12:59.539
that wanted to keep polluting,
they didn't want to invest in

00:12:59.539 --> 00:13:01.480
the technology,
perhaps a scrubber.

00:13:01.480 --> 00:13:05.639
So this idea is very similar to
what's being discussed with

00:13:05.639 --> 00:13:08.964
respect to carbon trading,
but also it has great

00:13:08.964 --> 00:13:11.868
similarity to these other
concepts about ecosystem

00:13:11.868 --> 00:13:12.580
services.
 

00:13:12.580 --> 00:13:16.182
So that the underlying
requirement is there has to be

00:13:16.182 --> 00:13:20.408
some sort of a legal threshold
that's easily identifiable,

00:13:20.408 --> 00:13:24.274
and some sort of a trading
formula that is set up in order

00:13:24.274 --> 00:13:26.240
for these to be functional.
 

00:13:26.240 --> 00:13:30.015
So here is a suite of different
kinds of management

00:13:30.015 --> 00:13:31.149
alternatives.
 

00:13:31.149 --> 00:13:35.900
Now, as you think about the
vulnerability of property and

00:13:35.900 --> 00:13:40.653
life in the coastal zone,
I want you to be thinking about

00:13:40.653 --> 00:13:42.350
it ecologically.
 

00:13:42.350 --> 00:13:45.774
I want you to think about what
principles of ecology or

00:13:45.774 --> 00:13:49.389
understanding of ecosystems and
how they're structured and

00:13:49.389 --> 00:13:52.178
function and how they change
over time,

00:13:52.178 --> 00:13:55.470
what principles should you have
in mind as you're thinking about

00:13:55.470 --> 00:13:57.820
selection among these different
strategies?

00:13:57.820 --> 00:14:01.422
And I think that one of the
intellectual pioneers of this

00:14:01.422 --> 00:14:04.960
idea of tying the science of
ecology with law that would

00:14:04.960 --> 00:14:07.918
somehow control the way that we
use land,

00:14:07.918 --> 00:14:11.379
it was pioneered by Ian McHarg,
a relatively famous landscape

00:14:11.379 --> 00:14:14.090
architect at the University of
Pennsylvania,

00:14:14.090 --> 00:14:19.062
and the individual that really
I give credit to for inspiring

00:14:19.062 --> 00:14:21.879
me to do what I do with my life.
 

00:14:21.879 --> 00:14:25.025
Now, I want you to think just
carefully about population

00:14:25.025 --> 00:14:27.200
concentrations in the United
States.

